         b'=0 CELLPADDING=5 CELLSPACING=5>\r\n<tr><td><font color=#000088'
         b'>\r\n\r\n<P><BR>\r\nLook at the faces above. \r\nSuppose that each o'
         b'f these somehow represented the overall financial state of a company'
         b', \r\nin which ones would you invest? Suppose each one represented'
         b' the global data representing the \r\ncredit-worthiness of an indi'
         b'vidual who had applied for a loan, to which ones would you grant the'
         b' loan? \r\n<p>\r\nThe Empathic Visualisation Algorithm (EVA) support'
         b's this kind of  analysis.\r\nIn fact the faces above were generate'
         b'd from the financial data of companies (apart from the last two\r'
         b'\nin the list which illustrate how the faces are displayed). \r\n<p'
         b'>\r\nThe EVA requires two inputs \x96 first the actual data, whic'
         b'h is any data matrix of n rows on k variables.\r\nFor example, thi'
         b's could be n companies measured on k financial indicators. Typically'
         b' both n and k would\r\nbe large (though with n greater than k). Se'
         b'cond, the data is always examined for a purpose \x96 let\x92s call'
         b' \r\nthe person or people who make decisions on the basis of the d'
         b'ata the \x91users\x92. The user has a set of \r\ngoals in mind when '
         b'examining the data. The goals are typically prioritised (though they'
         b' do not have to\r\n be). What the EVA does is to provide a mapping'
         b' so that the most important goals are transformed into \r\nthe mos'
         b't important emotional facial expressions. For example, suppose the m'
         b'ost important goal when \r\nexamining a group of companies is that'
         b' profitability must be above a certain percentage of turnover. \r'
         b'\nLet\x92s suppose that this particular goal is mapped into \x91hap'
         b'piness\x92. Then the higher the profit in \r\nrelation to turnove'
         b'r, the more happy the face will look. On the other hand, suppose tha'
         b't staff turnover \r\nis mapped to anxiety. Then the greater the st'
         b'aff turnover, the greater the anxiety shown on the face.\r\nIt is '
         b'then possible to get a face that in its overall aspect, looks happy,'
         b' but with a trace of anxiety\r\nshowing through. Since humans are '
         b'experts (without training!) of picking up emotional expression in fa'
         b'ces,\r\n a single glance will show that such a company is overall '
         b'doing very well in profitability, but at the \r\nsame time there i'
         b's cause for concern in the higher than wanted staff turnover. Of cou'
         b'rse this is a simple \r\nexample to get the idea across \x96 but '
         b'this can be generalised to a larger combinations of variables (and m'
         b'any \r\ndifferent applications). <P> </font></td></tr></table>'
